@NODE "WIZARD" "Wizard-Handler User Manual"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Description / The Sharp Wizard


@{b}Sharp Electronics Corporation@{ub} manufactures a line of electronic
organizers known as @{i}"Wizard"@{ui} organizers.

The Wizard firmware is composed of applications such as address books, a ToDo
list and a Scrapbook for drawings.  While the software to manipulate the
data for the various applications resides in the Wizard's ROM, the data
itself is stored in the Wizard's internal RAM.  Some Wizard models can also
store data on a removable memory card.

The Wizard stores the data for the applications in individual @{"files" link "FILES"},
in a manner very similar to the MS-DOS filing system.  In normal use this
fact is hidden from the user.

Wizards have two ways of communicating with other electronice devices: a
hard-wired serial connection and a wireless infra-red connection.  The
Wizard makes use of these methods to send and receive application data with
other Wizards, personal computers and other compatible devices.

The Wizard supports several communication protocols over either the serial
or infra-red communication channels.  It is possible to send or receive
a single entry or all entries from within an application.  The Wizard also
supports "PC-Link" mode, in which the Wizard becomes a file server for an
external device.

This is how @{"Wizard-Handler" link "WIZARDHANDLER"} accesses the Wizard.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "WIZARDHANDLER" "Wizard-Handler User Manual"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Description / Wizard-Handler


Wizard-Handler mounts your Wizard (in its PC-Link mode) as an Amiga device,
allowing you to read the Wizard's files, modify them and write them back
using standard AmigaDOS calls.  If your Wizard has a memory card inserted
in it, Wizard-Handler will mount that as an additional device.

All the ways in which you currently interact with Amiga devices should work
with Wizard-Handler, including Workbench and file manipulation programs
such as DirectoryOpus.

However, the files which the Wizard makes available are not text files, and
are not easily modified without an understanding of the data format.

Wizard-Handler is merely a filing system, not a data converter.
Wizard-Handler will be immediately useful to you as a way of backing-up and
restoring the contents of your Wizard.

It is hoped that other programs will be written that will convert the
Wizard's files into a format that allows them to be edited on the Amiga.

Such work is already underway by the @{"author" link "AUTHOR"} and another
programmer.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "DISTRIBUTION" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
