Wizard-Handler is shareware.  The fee is US$10 per user.  For an additional
US$15 you can obtain the source code, several thousand lines in SAS
`C' (v6.56), comprising high-level handler, mid-level translation and
low-level I/O routines.

Send your shareware contribution to the @{"author" link "AUTHOR"}.


Wizard-Handler may not be included in or distributed with a commercial
product without the express written consent of the author. Permission is
hereby granted to distribute the Wizard-Handler executable and
documentation via electronic means and in Amiga software collections for
which no charge or only a small amount of money more than production costs
is charged.

The source code for Wizard-Handler may not be redistributed.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "HARDWARE" "Wizard-Handler User Manual"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Installation / Hardware


The Wizard's serial port (labeled "COMPUTER LINK" on some units) consists
of a bi-directional TTL-level (Transistor-to-Transistor Logic) serial
interface.

Connecting to devices with a standard RS-232 serial interface (such as the
Amiga) requires a level-converting adapter.

Such adapters are available from several sources.  Two of them are:

Sharp Electronics Corporation 800.642-2122 (24 Hours; ask for Wizard
accessories).  World wide web: http://www.sharp-usa.com.  Their model CE-133T
is designed to connect a Wizard to an IBM PC, but will work with the Amiga.
As of February 1996 it retailed for US$100.

Rupp Technologies, 800.852-7877 (MST; UTC-7).  World wide web:
http://www.rupp.com.  Their "RuppLynx cable" (also designed for the IBM PC)
sells for US$45.


Follow the directions that came with your Wizard serial cable to connect
your Wizard to your Amiga.

The @{"author" link "AUTHOR"} is working on "infrared.device", which will
allow Wizard-Handler to communicate via the Wizard's infrared port.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "SOFTWARE" "Wizard-Handler User Manual"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Installation / Software


Wizard-Handler requires AmigaOS 2.0 (or higher).

Copy "Wizard-Handler" to the Sys:l directory.

To mount Wizard-Handler from the Shell, type,
"Mount Wiz: from MountList_Wiz".

  or

To have Wizard-Handler mounted when your Amiga boots up,
copy "Wiz" and "Wiz.info" to Sys:Devs/DOSDrivers.

  or

To be able to start up Wizard-Handler only when you want it,
copy "Wiz" and "Wiz.info" to Sys:Storage/DOSDrivers.
Double-click on the "Wiz" icon to mount Wizard-Handler.


You may need to change the information in either "Wiz" or "MountList_Wiz"
(depending upon which method of mounting you choose from above) to specify
the serial device and unit which you would like Wizard-Handler to use.

The serial communications parameters are conveyed in the CONTROL entry.  The
communication parameters supported by the Wizard's PC-Link mode are 9600
Baud, eight (8) data bits, one (1) stop bit and odd parity.  This results in
a MountList entry of:

    Control = "8O1N"


The RESERVED entry allows you to choose whether the Wizard will download
the contents of all its files immediately or only as each file is actually
accessed.  This difference is provided to overcome a @{"limitation" link "LIMITATIONS"}
in the way the Wizard handles files.  If RESERVED is set to 1 (the
default) files are only downloaded as needed.  This allows the
Wizard-Handler software to be mounted quickly.  This mode is best used
when only certain files (whose names are know in advance) will be
accessed, and especially if not all files will be accessed.  If RESERVED
is set to 2, all files will be downloaded as soon as Wizard-Handler is
mounted.  This can take over three minutes for a full 256K Wizard, to over
ten minutes for a full 512K Wizard with full memory card.  This mode is
best used when you are going to be examining the contents of many files
using the WorkBench, or with a directory utility such as Directory Opus.

If you always intend to backup (or restore) the entire contents of your
Wizard (using either AmigaDOS' Copy or an archiver such as LHA) then it
does not matter which mode you use, although mode 2 (download all files
immediately) will give slightly better efficiency as it downloads the files
in one large transfer rather than with a transfer for each file.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "MOUNTING" "Wizard-Handler User Manual"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Accessing the Wizard's Files / Mounting the Wizard


Connect your Wizard to your Amiga as specified in the @{"hardware" link "HARDWARE"} installation
section.

Turn on your Wizard.

If you have password-protected your Wizard, enter your password and then
unlock the Wizard by selecting "Unlock Organizer" from the Tools menu.

Note: The Wizard must be unlocked in order for PC-Link to function.

Put your Wizard into PC-Link mode by selecting "PC-Link" from the
Peripherals menu.  Even if your Wizard's screen is not functioning, it is
still possible to put it into PC-Link mode @{"blind" link "BLIND"}.

On your Amiga, either double-click on the "Wiz" icon or type "Mount Wiz"
from a Shell.

The Wizard-Handler's icon will appear on the Workbench once the volume is
mounted.  If the Wizard contains a memory card, a second icon will also
appear.

From Workbench, open the "Wiz:" icon and select "Window/Show/All Files" from
the Workbench menu.

From the Shell, type, "CD Wiz:" and "list".

Be patient!  The PC-Link has several @{"limitations" link "LIMITATIONS"}
which slow down transfers.

You can greatly speed up the time it takes the Wizard to be mounted by
changing an entry in the mountlist.  See @{"software" link "SOFTWARE"} or
the actual mountlist file for more information.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "REMOVING" "Wizard-Handler User Manual"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Accessing the Wizard's Files / Removing Wizard-Handler

Wizard-Handler can be completely removed from the system.  AmigaDOS does
not provide a standard command for this ("Assign REMOVE" does not notify
the handler and is therefore incomplete) so a kludge has been provided.

Use the "Relabel" command to rename the mounted volume to the special
name of "DIE" (this was chosen to correspond with the ACTION_DIE handler
packet which will also work if sent directly).

For example:

Relabel WIZ: DIE


If there are currently any open and modified files on the volume this
will fail.  It is possible to force the removal by renaming the volume
to "FORCE" instead.

Relabel WIZ: FORCE

This may, however, leave partial files on the Wizard.


Notes:

1.  Though the "Relabel" command refers to only one volume, if both the
    Wizard and a memory card are mounted, both will disappear when
    Wizard-Handler removes itself.

2.  Wizard-Handler does not support the "Relabel" command for the
    normal use of renaming a volume.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "WARNINGS" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Data Integrity / Warnings

This section describes some of the horrible things you can do to your
Wizard to confuse it.  Note well that such actions will likely lead to the
need to reset the Wizard, and may lead to data loss.

The Wizard's internal software is very robust, but it is possible to
confuse it to the point where it will not function.  Mixing a single
application's ".BOX" and ".IDX" files from different backups (e.g. today's
"TEL1.BOX" and last week's "TEL1.IDX") should be avoided if there have been
changes to that application in the interim.

The Wizard must have room for its internal files.  If you delete any of the
Wizard's internal @{"files" link "FILES"} the Wizard will attempt to create
a newly initialized replacement when you exit PC-Link mode (or power-cycle
your Wizard).  If there is not enough room in the Wizard's memory to
successfully create the replacement file the Wizard may not be able to
function.

While Wizard-Handler is running, do not take your Wizard out of PC-Link
mode, modify any of the files on it and then put it back into PC-Link
mode.  Doing so will cause Wizard-Handler and the Wizard to be out of sync,
which will likely lead to problems.  If you must use the wizard in such a
way, first @{"remove" link "REMOVING"} Wizard-Handler and later re-mount it.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "SECURITY" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Data Integrity / Security

There are several causes for concern about the security of the information
contained in your Wizard.

When it creates a new entry in its memory, the Wizard appears not to clear
the memory.  This results in snippets of old data being retained in new
files.  The data is not constrained to the same application, so (for
example) the notebook application may contain previously deleted phone
numbers.  The "abandoned" information is not viewable from any of the
Wizard's applications, only when the application's data is downloaded to
the host computer.  Keep this in mind if you archive your Wizard information
on a network.

Similarly, it appears that the Wizard stores the user's password in clear
text in the CLIP.SYS file when the unit is first unlocked.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "LIMITATIONS" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Data Integrity / Limitations

There are several serious deficiencies in the way the Wizard PC-Link
interface was implemented.  Understanding them can help prevent the loss of
data as well as give an appreciation of why Wizard communication is so slow.

There is no way to ascertain the size of a file on the Wizard without
receiving the entire file.  This is the reason that the first directory
scan is so slow; the entire contents of the Wizard must be downloaded in
order to know the file sizes.

The "I/R Protocol" used for both infrared and hard-wired communications has
a fair amount of overhead.  This reduces the 9600 Baud transmission rate to
well below its potential.

The Wizard reports that it is completely empty (0% full) even though it
contains non-empty system files.  Free space is related to user data, not
Wizard-internal data.  The one exception to this is that there is an
overhead of 34 bytes for each new file created, and that will be subtracted
from the total "free space".

@ENDNODE


@NODE "ARCHIVE" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Making use of the Data / Archiving


To backup the data on your Wizard, copy all the files on it to another
device.  From AmigaDOS you can use the Copy command.  It is also possible to
use archiving tools such as "Lha".

Restoring the data requires copying the previously saved files back to the
Wizard.

Important Note:
The Wizard constructs part of the "Schedule" application's data each time it
is turned on by examining other applications.  For example, the anniversary
application data (which is specified in forms such as "third Sunday in
March" is converted into actual dates when the unit is turned on.  It is
recommended that after you have finished restoring system files to the
Wizard you @{"remove" link "REMOVING"} Wizard-Handler, release the Wizard
from PC-Link mode (there may be a delay as the Wizard appears to do some
amount of file validation here), shut the Wizard off and then allow it to
re-initialize the data by turning it "ON" again.

See @{"files" link "FILES"} for information on backing up and restoring a
single application.

Note also that there is some Wizard information which is not retained in
files and hence is not be archivable, for example the current time and user
settings such as the means of communications for PC-Link, unit-to-unit
transfer.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "FILES" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Making use of the Data / Files


Each of the Wizard's applications requires several files to describe its
data.  Typically, the .BOX files contain the data, while the .IDX and .FDX
files describe the format and labeling of the data.

To backup and restore a single application you must backup and restore all
of the files associated with that application.

Application    Data file(s)            Index files(s)

Anniversary 1  ANN1.BOX                ANN1.IDX
Anniversary 2  ANN2.BOX                ANN2.IDX

Notebook       NOTE.BOX                NOTE.IDX
UserFile 1     USER1.BOX USERINF1.BOX  USER1.IDX
UserFile 2     USER2.BOX USERINF2.BOX  USER2.IDX
UserFile 3     USER3.BOX USERINF3.BOX  USER3.IDX

Telephone 1    TEL1.BOX TELINF1.BOX    TEL1.IDX
Telephone 2    TEL2.BOX TELINF2.BOX    TEL2.IDX
Telephone 3    TEL3.BOX TELINF3.BOX    TEL3.IDX

To Do          TODO.BOX TODOCG.BOX     TODODAT.IDX
                                       TODOPRI.IDX
                                       TODOCTG.IDX

Schedule       SCHEDULE.BOX            SCHEDULE.IDX
Outline        OUTLINE.BOX             OUTLINE.IDX
Scrapbook      SCRAP.BOX               SCRAP.IDX

Word Key       USER.BOX                USER.IDX
Terminal       TERMINAL.BOX            MODEM.BOX

System         OPENING.BOX SYSTEM.INF
Clipboard      CLIP.SYS
Filer          FILER.BOX               INBOX*A.FDX - INBOX*L.FDX
                                       FILER*A.FDX - FILER*L.FDX
Money          *.BOX                   *.TDX
(OZ-5x00 models only)


Notes:
The DISK.INFO file that appears in the Wizard's filelist is created by
Wizard-Handler and (initially) only appears on the Amiga; the file is not
created on the Wizard.  If you attempt to write to this file (this includes
"snapshoting" it from the Workbench) it @{i}will@{ui} be written to the
Wizard.  This allows you to customize your Wizard/Amiga environment.
If you later delete the DISK.INFO file from your Wizard, Wizard-Handler will
(when next mounting the Wizard) again create the Amiga-only DISK.INFO file.

The INBOX and FILER ".FDX" filenames contain a character with the high bit
set.  Workbench will complain if you attempt to manipulate these files.
The Shell, as well as archiving tools such as "Lha" will handle these files
without a problem.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "INTERP" "Wizard-Handler User Manual"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Making Use of the Data / Interpreting the Wizard's files.


Wizard-Handler is merely a filing system, not a data converter.  It was
written in the hope that others would write Amiga programs to interpret the
application data.

With a little detective work you may be able to interpret the format of the
application files on the Wizard.

If you prefer, you can request documentation directly from Sharp.  Note that
the documentation was written by software engineers for software engineers
and is therefore sometimes unclear.

Sharp Wizard Developer Support is the sole provider of documentation
describing the format of Wizard application files.  To request such
documentation, contact Ms. Veena S. Agarwal (agarwalv@sharpsec.com) at
+1 201.529-8789 (EST; UTC+5).  Request the following document:

Sharp Wizard OZ-9000 Series Electronic Organizer
     Serial Communication Protocol
            Version 1.1
          1 February 1993

I suggest that you be prepared to send a letter describing your intended
application.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "BLIND" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Making Use of the Data / Blind PC-Link Mode


The Wizard's screen is fragile, and undue force can damage it.  A damaged
screen may prevent the user from accessing the Wizard's data.  In this case,
the only recourse may be to archive the data to the Amiga and restore it to
the Wizard once the screen is fixed.

However, with the broken screen it can be difficult to put the Wizard into
PC-Link mode.  The following instructions will tell you how to do it.

@{" 95x0 " link "BLIND_9500"} - For the OZ-95x0 series.

@{" 96x0 " link "BLIND_9600"} - For the OZ-96x0 series.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "BLIND_9500" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Blind PC-Link Mode / 95x0 series


These instruction refer to the 9500 and 9520 Wizard models.

Read through the following directions before actually attempting them.  The
steps for setting the PC-Link path differ depending upon the existence and
type of IC card inserted in your Wizard; you may choose to determine these
facts before you perform the procedure.


A blank screen may just mean that the @{"batteries" link "BATTERIES"} are
low or that the screen's @{"contrast" link "CONTRAST"} is turned down.


1. @{"Function test" link "FUNCTIONAL"} - Determine if the Wizard's processor is functional.

 At this point your Wizard should be known to function.

2. @{"Power-up" link "POWER"} - Turn the unit on and enter the password.

 At this point your Wizard should be on.

3. @{"Unlock" link "UNLOCK"} - Unlock the Wizard.

 At this point your Wizard should be unlocked.

4. @{"PERIPHERALS" link "PERIPHERALS_9500"} - Set the PC-Link Path.

 At this point the PC-Link path should be set to "VIA DIRECT CABLE".

5. @{"PC-Link" link "PC-LINK"} - Put the Wizard into PC-Link mode.

 At this point the Wizard should be in PC-Link mode.  Mount Wizard-Handler as usual.

 Note that the Wizard will remain in PC-Link mode indefinitely; it will not
 shut off after ten minutes as it normally does.  You must quit PC-Link mode
 before you can turn off the Wizard.

6. @{"Quitting" link "QUITTING"} - Quitting PC-Link mode.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "BLIND_9600" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "CONTENTS"

Blind PC-Link Mode / 96x0 series


These instruction refer to the 9600 and 9600II Wizard models.

Read through the following directions before actually attempting them.  The
steps for setting the PC-Link path differ depending upon the existence and
type of IC card inserted in your Wizard; you may choose to determine these
facts before you perform the procedure.


A blank screen may just mean that the @{"batteries" link "BATTERIES"} are
low or that the screen's @{"contrast" link "CONTRAST"} is turned down.


1. @{"Function test" link "FUNCTIONAL"} - Determine if the Wizard's processor is functional.

 At this point your Wizard should be known to function.

2. @{"Power-up" link "POWER"} - Turn the unit on and enter the password.

 At this point your Wizard should be on.

3. @{"Unlock" link "UNLOCK"} - Unlock the Wizard.

 At this point your Wizard should be unlocked.

4. @{"PERIPHERALS" link "PERIPHERALS_9600"} - Set the PC-Link Path.

 At this point the PC-Link path should be set to "VIA DIRECT CABLE".

5. @{"PC-Link" link "PC-LINK"} - Put the Wizard into PC-Link mode.

 At this point the Wizard should be in PC-Link mode.  Mount Wizard-Handler as usual.

 Note that the Wizard will remain in PC-Link mode indefinitely; it will not
 shut off after ten minutes as it normally does.  You must quit PC-Link mode
 before you can turn off the Wizard.

6. @{"Quitting" link "QUITTING"} - Quitting PC-Link mode.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "BATTERIES" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Are the Batteries Low?


At this point you may wish to first try changing the Wizard's operating
batteries.  Instructions for doing this can be found in the Wizard manual.

Note: @{b}Do not remove the (disc-shaped) Lithium memory battery or the
      Wizard will lose it's memory!).@{ub}

@ENDNODE


@NODE "CONTRAST" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Is the Contrast Turned Down?


Attempt to bring up the "Adjust LCD Contrast" screen with the following:

    It is assumed that the unit is off.
    Press the MENU button, and while holding it down press the ON button.
    Release the ON button but continue to hold the MENU button down for
    three seconds.  Release the MENU button.  Press and hold the up-arrow
    cursor key (not the PREV key) in an attempt to increase the contrast.

If the above step is successful, there is no need to continue.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "FUNCTIONAL" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Determine if the Wizard is Functional


Press and release the OFF button to make sure the unit is off.
Press and release the ON button to turn the unit on.

Wait several seconds for the unit to initialize.

Repeat the following step several times (it attempts to enable/disable the
key "beep"):

    Press and release the "2nd" key and then press and release the
    left-arrow cursor key.

If you hear the Wizard beep every other time you press the "2nd" key, then
the Wizard is still functioning, and can likely be put into PC-Link mode.

@{"Next step" link "UNLOCK"} - Move on to the next step.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "POWER" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Power-up the Wizard


If the Wizard is not already on from the previous step, turn it on now with:
    Press and release the ON button to turn the unit on.
    Wait several seconds for the unit to initialize.

Press and release the SHIFT key several times.  If you hear a beep each
time, skip the following step.

    Press and release the "2nd" key and then press and release the
    left-arrow cursor key.

Again, press and release the SHIFT key several times.  If you still don't
hear beeps, either the Wizard is not on or is not operational, or the
batteries are dead.

@{"Next step" link "UNLOCK"} - Move on to the next step.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "UNLOCK" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Unlock the Wizard


If you have set your Wizard to request a password, you will have to enter it now:

    Type your password and press and release the "ENTER" key.
    Press and release the "2nd" key.  Press and release the down-arrow
    cursor key.  (This invokes the "Unlock Organizer" screen.)
    Type your password again and press and release the "ENTER" key.

The next step depends upon your model of Wizard:

@{" 95x0 " link "PERIPHERALS_9500"} - For the 95x0 Series.
@{" 96x0 " link "PERIPHERALS_9600"} - For the 95x0 Series.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "PERIPHERALS_9500" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Peripherals / 95x0 Series


The PC-Link path must be set to "VIA DIRECT CABLE".  The following steps
will insure that this is the case.

    Press and release the "2nd" key and then press and release the "E" key.
    Press and release the up-arrow cursor key.
    Press and release the "ENTER" key.
    Press and release the up-arrow cursor key exactly five times.
    Press and release the "ENTER" key.
    Press and release the up-arrow cursor key exactly once.
    Press and release the "ENTER" key.


(A note for advanced users: if you have a device connected to your Wizard's
serial line which indicates the logic-level of the serial lines, you will
notice that the Wizard enables the serial port during PC-Link even if the
PC-Link path is set to "VIA INFRARED".)

@{"Next step" link "PC-LINK"} - Move on to the next step.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "PERIPHERALS_9600" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Peripherals / 96x0 Series


Note that one of the following steps depends upon the existence and type of
IC card inserted in your Wizard.

The PC-Link path must be set to "VIA DIRECT CABLE".  The following steps
will insure that this is the case.

    Press and release the "2nd" key and then press and release the "E" key
    (labeled "Peripherals").

    If there is a memory card inserted in your Wizard:
        Press and release the down-arrow cursor key exactly four times.
    If there is no card, or a non-memory (i.e. application) card inserted
    your Wizard:
        Press and release the down-arrow cursor key exactly five times.

    Press and release the "ENTER" key.
    Press and release the up-arrow cursor key exactly once.
    Press and release the "ENTER" key.


(A note for advanced users: if you have a device connected to your Wizard's
serial line which indicates the logic-levels of the serial lines, you will
notice that the Wizard enables the serial port during PC-Link even if the
PC-Link path is set to "VIA INFRARED".)

@{"Next step" link "PC-LINK"} - Move on to the next step.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "PC-LINK" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Activating PC-Link Mode


    Press and release the "2nd" key and then press and release the "E" key.
    Press and release the down-arrow cursor key exactly once.
    Press and release the "ENTER" key.

At this point your Wizard should be in PC-Link mode.  Follow the directions
for starting Wizard-Handler.

Note that @{"quitting" link "QUITTING"} PC-Link mode is required before you
can turn off the Wizard.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "QUITTING" "Wizard-Handler User Documentation"
@TOC "BLIND"

Blind PC-Link Mode / Quitting PC-Link Mode


Press and release the ON button to leave PC-Link mode.
Wait several seconds for the Wizard to return to normal.

If you wish to turn the Wizard off, press and release the OFF button now.

@ENDNODE


